      "The intersectionality of women's experiences adds important nuance to Women's Day conversations. Women of different races, castes, classes, abilities, sexual orientations, and geographic locations face overlapping and distinct challenges. Dalit women in India, Black women in America, refugee women in Syria, indigenous women in Latin America — each group's experience of gender inequality is shaped by its intersection with other forms of discrimination. Recognizing this complexity makes Women's Day celebrations more authentic and the demands for equality more comprehensive.",
