      "Wedding traditions across the world reflect fascinating cultural values. In Jewish weddings, the groom breaks a glass underfoot, symbolizing the destruction of the Temple in Jerusalem and the fragility of relationships. In Chinese weddings, the Tea Ceremony shows respect to both families. In Nigerian Yoruba weddings, the groom and his groomsmen must prove themselves in a public taste test. In Japanese Shinto weddings, the couple takes three sips each from three cups of sake (San-san-kudo) symbolizing the binding of families. In Scottish weddings, the tradition of hand-fasting (literally tying the couple's hands together) gave rise to the phrase 'tying the knot.'",
