      "Baby showers are a beautiful tradition celebrating the upcoming arrival of a new life. The custom of showering expectant parents with gifts, advice, and blessings dates back to ancient civilizations — the ancient Egyptians and Greeks held celebrations for expecting mothers. The modern baby shower as a party format emerged in post-World War II America, coinciding with the baby boom era. Today, baby showers are celebrated worldwide, with each culture adding its own unique traditions — from the Indian Godh Bharai and Seemantham ceremonies to the British 'babymoon,' the Japanese 'Obi Iwai' (sash celebration), and the South Korean 'Baek-il' (100th day celebration after birth).",
      "Traditional Indian baby shower ceremonies are among the most culturally rich and symbolically meaningful pregnancy celebrations in the world. Known as Godh Bharai in North India, Seemantham in South India, Shaad in Bengali culture, and Valaikappu in Tamil tradition, these ceremonies typically take place in the seventh or eighth month of pregnancy. The mother-to-be is dressed in special new attire, her lap is filled with fruits, sweets, and gifts (symbolizing fertility and abundance), and traditional songs celebrating motherhood and the coming child are sung. Elders share blessings and advice, and the community comes together to support and celebrate the expectant mother.",
